<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="311" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1290,1315]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<emphasis box="[517,584,1291,1314]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">tenuis</emphasis>
(= thin) and 
<emphasis box="[732,825,1291,1314]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">spinatus</emphasis>
(= spined), for the presence of very thin spines on the apical actine of the tetractines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" box="[199,609,1362,1387]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,287,1362,1387]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Colour.</emphasis>
white in life and in ethanol.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="311" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1398,1423]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Morphology.</emphasis>
Consistency fragile and friable. Cormus massive, formed by thin, regular and tightly anastomosed tubes (
<figureCitation box="[376,435,1434,1459]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
A). The specimens were fragmented, therefore it was not possible to determine accurately the absence of water-collecting tubes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1506,1531]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Anatomy.</emphasis>
No cells with granules were found. The skeleton is composed of triactines, tetractines, tripods and tetrapods, which look like large triactines and tetractines, respectively (
<figureCitation box="[952,1013,1542,1567]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
B). Triactines and tetractines occur in approximately the same proportion, or tetractines are a little more abundant. Tetrapods are less abundant than tripods
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1650,1675]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Spicules</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[313,414,1650,1675]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Figure 3</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[429,518,1650,1675]" captionStart="TABLE 4" captionStartId="12.[151,239,544,567]" captionText="TABLE 4. Spicule measurements of Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. (H = holotype; P = paratype)." pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Table 4</tableCitation>
). Triactines: Equiangular and equiradiate. Actines are conical and straight, with tips varying from sharp to blunt (
<figureCitation box="[521,581,1686,1711]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
Tetractines: Equiangular and equiradiate. Actines are conical and straight, with tips sharp to blunt (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1399,1722,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
D). The apical actine has spines organized in several (five or more) rows radially disposed. They are very abundant, long and thin (
<figureCitation box="[313,373,1794,1819]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
Tripods: Equiangular and equiradiate or subregular. They look like large triactines with conical, stout actines and blunt tips (
<figureCitation box="[318,378,1866,1891]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
Tetrapods: Equiangular and equiradiate or subregular. They look like large tetractines with conical, stout actines and blunt tips (
<figureCitation box="[403,463,1938,1963]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1798]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1755]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 3. Borojevia tenuispinata sp. nov. A—Holotype after fixation. B—Section. C—Triactine. D—Tetractine. E— Tetractine (ap: apical actine with spines). F—Tripod. G—Tetrapod." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Fig 3</figureCitation>
G). The apical actine has spines similar to those of the tetractines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1038,2035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,299,1974,1999]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Ecology.</emphasis>
Specimens were found from 
<quantity box="[629,735,1975,1999]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" unit="m" value="19.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="8.0">8 to 30 m</quantity>
of depth. Some specimens were associated with other sponges and algae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847814/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="312" targetBox="[151,1436,193,1755]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1776,1829]" pageId="11" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,1776,1798]" pageId="11" pageNumber="312">FIGURE 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Klautau, 2017" authorityName="Klautau" authorityYear="2017" box="[292,528,1777,1798]" class="Calcarea" family="Clathrinidae" genus="Borojevia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="11" pageNumber="312" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="tenuispinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[292,528,1777,1798]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="312">Borojevia tenuispinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[540,627,1776,1798]" pageId="11" pageNumber="312" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[540,627,1776,1798]" pageId="11" pageNumber="312">sp. nov.</emphasis>
